After parting ways with Hinata and the others, I went to the burned-out ruins of the mountain hut, and found that the old wood and paper burned particularly well.

Behind them were a sooty stone stove and the remains of an underground warehouse.

I searched for the burnt remains, but I couldn't find the cloth bag containing the coins given to me by the elf.

Apparently, the villagers searched for houses and stole anything valuable before setting the mountain hut on fire.

I had nowhere to go back to, so I went back to my house in the village, but I should have stopped.

The people in the village look at me even more strangely than before, probably because they feel guilty for stealing something that belonged to me.

It's strange that the person who had the item stolen gets glared at by the person who stole it.

"...I don't have any regrets in this village anymore."

Why don't we set this house on fire?

That thought crosses my mind.

If a house were to burn down on a windy day, the fire would spread to other places, even from this house on the outskirts of the village, and it would be terrible.

If that happens, I wonder if my drinking will go down a little.

But I didn't choose that.

... Everything didn't matter anymore.

I was so indecisive that I couldn't even take Hinata's hand at that time, so how could I choose something as drastic as setting the house on fire?

All I can do is run away.

Just like I ran away from the village into the forest that day.

